Here is an updated version of the previous program that handles wrapping around for characters that exceed the valid ASCII range:

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.BufferedWriter;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.io.FileWriter;
import java.io.IOException;

public class FileEncryption {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String inputFile = "input.txt";
        String outputFile = "output.txt";
        int key = 3; // Caesar cipher key

        try (BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(inputFile));
             BufferedWriter writer = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter(outputFile))) {

            int character;
            while ((character = reader.read()) != -1) {
                char encryptedChar = (char)(character + key);
                if (encryptedChar > 127) {
                    encryptedChar = (char)(encryptedChar - 127 + 32); // wrap around
                }
                writer.write(encryptedChar);
            }

            System.out.println("File encrypted successfully!");

        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("An error occurred: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

In this updated program:
- If the encrypted character exceeds the range of valid ASCII characters (0 to 127), it wraps around to the beginning of the range by subtracting 127 and adding 32. This will ensure that the encryption stays within the valid range of ASCII characters.

